### Issue 4: CSS Class Collision When Same Widget Runs on Multiple Pages (Global)

**Problem:** You mentioned this same code (with different selectors/content) will run on Hotels, Shop, and Sightseeing confirmation pages. All variants use the same `id="stay-experience-widget"` and identical CSS class names (`.sew-card`, `.sew-wrapper`, etc.). If two variants somehow load on the same page (e.g., a combined confirmation), the duplicate-ID guard at line 4 will block the second widget entirely, and shared class names will cause style conflicts.

**Solution:** Parameterize the widget ID and CSS prefix per page type:
```js
var WIDGET_ID = "stay-experience-widget-cabs"; // unique per variant
var CSS_PREFIX = "sew-cabs"; // or "sew-hotels", "sew-shop", etc.

if (document.getElementById(WIDGET_ID)) return;
container.id = WIDGET_ID;
```
Or if only one widget per page is guaranteed, at minimum use distinct IDs per variant to allow independent caching/debugging.

